<div class="container">
  <h1>🔐 How Will I Know That I’m Hacked?</h1>
  <p><strong>By T20 CLASSIC TECH</strong><br>🛡️ Stay Safe | 💡 Stay Informed | 📱 Protect Your Data</p>

  <h2>🚨 1. Unusual Activity on Your Accounts</h2>
  <p><strong>What to Look For:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Unknown logins or devices</li>
    <li>Password reset emails or alerts you didn’t trigger</li>
    <li>Strange messages sent to your contacts</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Why This Happens:</strong> Hackers might’ve used phishing or leaked credentials to access your account.</p>
  <p><strong>What to Do:</strong> Change your password, log out all sessions, and enable 2FA.</p>

  <h2>📵 2. Device Slowing Down or Acting Weird</h2>
  <p><strong>What to Look For:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Battery drains quickly</li>
    <li>Unexplained overheating</li>
    <li>Pop-ups or strange behavior</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Why This Happens:</strong> Malware or spyware may be running in the background.</p>
  <p><strong>What to Do:</strong> Use antivirus, uninstall unknown apps, and reboot or reset.</p>

  <h2>💸 3. Suspicious Financial Transactions</h2>
  <p><strong>What to Look For:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Unknown charges or deductions</li>
    <li>OTPs or confirmation messages not triggered by you</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Why This Happens:</strong> Your payment info may have been compromised.</p>
  <p><strong>What to Do:</strong> Block/freeze accounts, change online banking passwords, and contact support.</p>

  <h2>🧠 4. Changed Passwords or Settings</h2>
  <p><strong>What to Look For:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>You're locked out of your account</li>
    <li>Recovery email or phone changed</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Why This Happens:</strong> Hackers change recovery settings to take full control.</p>
  <p><strong>What to Do:</strong> Use account recovery or contact platform support immediately.</p>

  <h2>🐛 5. Unknown Apps or Files</h2>
  <p><strong>What to Look For:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Apps/files you don’t recognize</li>
    <li>High data or CPU usage</li>
    <li>Camera or mic activating on its own</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Why This Happens:</strong> Your device might have a trojan, spyware, or adware.</p>
  <p><strong>What to Do:</strong> Remove suspicious apps, run antivirus scans, and reset browser settings.</p>

  <h2>🛠️ Immediate Steps to Take</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Change all important passwords</li>
    <li>Enable Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)</li>
    <li>Run antivirus scans</li>
    <li>Log out of all active sessions</li>
    <li>Be cautious with public Wi-Fi and apps</li>
  </ul>

